### 2. How Panning Works

**There is no explicit mouse/touch pan (drag-to-pan).** There is no single-finger swipe pan handler. The only x/y offset changes happen as a side-effect of zooming (pinch or button zoom repositions x/y to keep the anchor point stable).

The `gestureHint` in the HUD (line 1344) says "Pinch to zoom, two fingers to pan" - but two-finger pan is only partially implemented: the pinch handler does update x/y based on the center point movement between frames (lines 802-805), so if two fingers move together (translate without pinching), the viewport x/y does shift. But there is no dedicated single-finger pan mode.

---

### 3. The `constrainViewport` Function (lines 89-114)

This is the core viewport constraint engine called on every viewport change:

```js
const constrainViewport = (candidate, stageWidth, stageHeight) => {
    const scale = clamp(candidate?.scale || 1, MIN_VIEWPORT_SCALE, MAX_VIEWPORT_SCALE);
    const scaledWidth = stageWidth * scale;
    const scaledHeight = stageHeight * scale;
    let minX = Math.min(0, stageWidth - scaledWidth);  // negative when zoomed in
    let maxX = 0;
    let minY = Math.min(0, stageHeight - scaledHeight);
    let maxY = 0;

    // When zoomed OUT (scaled smaller than viewport), center it
    if(scaledWidth <= stageWidth){
        const centeredX = (stageWidth - scaledWidth) / 2;
        minX = centeredX; maxX = centeredX;  // locks to center
    }
    if(scaledHeight <= stageHeight){
        const centeredY = (stageHeight - scaledHeight) / 2;
        minY = centeredY; maxY = centeredY;  // locks to center
    }

    return { scale, x: clamp(...), y: clamp(...) };
};
```

Key behavior:
- **Zoomed out (scale < 1):** Stage is centered and panning is locked (min=max).
- **Zoomed in (scale > 1):** x/y can range so you can pan to any edge, but not beyond.
- NOTE: `constrainViewport` is passed `viewportWidth` and `viewportHeight` (the rendered display size, `<= 560px`), NOT `stageWidth`/`stageHeight` (always 560). This is where the important distinction lies.

`updateViewport` wraps every viewport state update (lines 396-403) and always runs the candidate through `constrainViewport`:
```js
const updateViewport = (updater) => {
    setViewport((prev) => {
        const nextValue = typeof updater === "function" ? updater(prev) : updater;
        const constrained = constrainViewport(nextValue, viewportWidth, viewportHeight);
        viewportRef.current = constrained;
        return constrained;
    });
};
```

---

### 4. How `layerTransform` Is Applied to the Stage

The viewport is a logical offset on top of a "fit" transform. Two coordinate systems are combined:

```js
// Fit transform: scales stage (560px) to fit viewportWidth
const fitScale = viewportWidth > 0 ? viewportWidth / stageWidth : 1;
const fitOffsetX = (viewportWidth - stageWidth * fitScale) / 2;
const fitOffsetY = (viewportHeight - stageHeight * fitScale) / 2;

// Combined transform for Konva layers:
const layerTransform = {
    x: fitOffsetX + viewport.x,
    y: fitOffsetY + viewport.y,
    scaleX: fitScale * viewport.scale,
    scaleY: fitScale * viewport.scale
};
```

This is applied to every `<Layer>` in the Konva `<Stage>` (lines 1202, 1226, 1254). The `<Stage>` itself is sized to `viewportWidth x viewportHeight`, but the layers are drawn at `stageWidth x stageHeight` (560) coordinates then scaled down via `fitScale`, with an additional user zoom (`viewport.scale`) on top.

The `<Stage>` HTML element itself has no CSS transform. All scaling is done through Konva's layer transform system.

---

### 5. CSS Analysis

**`CanvasEditor.module.css` - Key Stage Styles:**

**.stageShell** (lines 37-56):
```css
.stageShell {
    position: relative;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 100%;
    box-sizing: border-box;
    border-radius: 18px;
    padding: 0 clamp(0.45rem, 0.9vw, 0.85rem);  /* horizontal padding only */
    flex-shrink: 0;
    overflow: hidden;   /* clips anything outside the shell */
    /* ... decorative background gradients and box-shadows ... */
}
```
The shell has `overflow: hidden`, which is why zoomed content can't bleed outside. It has responsive horizontal padding using `clamp`, which reduces the effective `shellWidth` measured by the ResizeObserver and thus `viewportWidth`.

**.stageFrame** (lines 111-119):
```css
.stageFrame {
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
    width: 100%;
    flex-shrink: 0;
    border-radius: 12px;
    overflow: hidden;        /* second clip layer */
    touch-action: pan-y;    /* allows vertical page scroll by default */
}
```
`overflow: hidden` here is a second clip boundary. `touch-action: pan-y` means the stage frame by default allows vertical scrolling, overridden to `none` when doodle mode is active.

**.stageHud** (lines 138-146):
```css
.stageHud {
    position: absolute;
    right: 0.8rem;
    bottom: 0.7rem;
    z-index: 2;
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.48rem;
}
```
Overlays the stage in the bottom-right corner. Contains:
- `.zoomBadge` - shows `{Math.round(viewport.scale * 100)}%` (the current zoom %)
- `.gestureHint` - only visible on mobile (`isMobileViewport`), shows "Pinch to zoom, two fingers to pan"

**.stage / .stageEditor** (lines 121-132):
```css
.stage {
    border-radius: 12px;
    touch-action: none;
}
.stageEditor {
    touch-action: pan-y;   /* overrides .stage for editor */
}
.isDoodleActive .stageEditor {
    touch-action: none;    /* when doodling, block all default touch */
}
```
The editor Stage overrides `touch-action` from `none` back to `pan-y` so users can scroll the page. This gets locked to `none` during doodle mode.

**`canvas.css`:**
This file contains an **older/legacy** CSS class set (`.canvas-stage-shell`, `.canvas-editor-root`, etc.). The current `CanvasEditor.jsx` does NOT use these classes - it uses CSS Modules from `CanvasEditor.module.css`. This legacy file likely exists from a previous iteration of the component and is imported via `import "./canvas.css"` at line 11, but the relevant classes (`.canvas-stage-shell`, etc.) are not referenced anywhere in the current JSX. The `.canvas-stage-shell` has `min-height: 220px` and `overflow: hidden`.

---

### 6. PieMenu Component

**File:** `PieMenu.jsx` + `PieMenu.module.css`

A radial context menu that appears on right-click or long-press (400ms timeout). It renders items in a circle of radius `RADIUS = 72px`.

**Trigger logic:**
- Right-click on `stageFrame` (line 1179-1183) opens at cursor position
- Long press (400ms `setTimeout`) on Stage opens at touch/mouse position (lines 863-870)

**Items:**
- In **doodle mode**: Undo, Redo, Clear
- With **selected object**: Delete, Duplicate, Front, Back, A+, A-, Rotate, Flip

**Animation:** Uses Framer Motion. Items spring-animate from scale 0 to 1 with staggered 30ms delays. The overlay covers the full `stageFrame` area (`position: absolute; inset: 0`), closes on click anywhere.

**Layout:** Items are positioned with `transform: translate(-50%, -50%)` centered on their computed polar coordinates. The `.ring` is `position: absolute` at `{left: position.x, top: position.y}`.

---

### 7. Minimap / Viewport Indicator

**There is no minimap.** The only viewport feedback is the `zoomBadge` in `stageHud` showing the zoom percentage as a pill-shaped label. No viewport position indicator, no minimap thumbnail, no scroll position indicator exists.

---

### Summary Table

| Feature | Status | Implementation |
|---|---|---|
| Zoom buttons | Yes | `zoomByStep()`, +/-14% per click, center-anchored |
| Pinch-to-zoom | Yes | `maybeHandlePinchMove()`, finger-midpoint anchored |
| Scroll-wheel zoom | No | Not implemented |
| Mouse drag pan | No | Not implemented |
| Two-finger pan | Partial | Side effect of pinch center movement |
| Zoom limits | Yes | 85% min, 300% max (`MIN/MAX_VIEWPORT_SCALE`) |
| Viewport constraints | Yes | `constrainViewport()` called on every update |
| Zoom display | Yes | `zoomBadge` in `stageHud` (bottom-right of shell) |
| Minimap | No | Does not exist |
| Reset view | Yes | `resetViewport()` button in toolbar |

