rectHeight = (stageHeight / viewport.scale) * miniScaleY =  MINI_H / viewport.scale
```

These simplify nicely - `rectWidth = MINI_W / viewport.scale` - no need to involve `fitScale` at all.

**Converting a minimap drag position back to a viewport offset:**

When the user drags the rect so its top-left is at minimap coordinate `(mx, my)`:

```
// Target top-left corner of visible area in stage coordinates:
targetStageX = mx / miniScaleX  =  mx * stageWidth / MINI_W
targetStageY = my / miniScaleY  =  my * stageHeight / MINI_H

// The viewport.x/y that achieves this (inverse of the formula above):
nextViewportX = -targetStageX * fitScale * viewport.scale
nextViewportY = -targetStageY * fitScale * viewport.scale
```

Since `fitScale = viewportWidth / stageWidth`, this becomes:

```
nextViewportX = -(mx / MINI_W) * viewportWidth * viewport.scale
nextViewportY = -(my / MINI_H) * viewportHeight * viewport.scale
```

This is passed directly to `updateViewport({ scale: viewport.scale, x: nextViewportX, y: nextViewportY })` - the existing `constrainViewport` call inside `updateViewport` will clamp it automatically.

---

### 2. DOM Placement

The minimap lives **inside `stageShell`**, as a sibling of `stageFrame`, `PieMenu`, and `stageHud`. It is positioned `absolute` in the **bottom-left** corner of `stageShell`, to avoid overlapping the existing `stageHud` zoom badge which is at `right: 0.8rem; bottom: 0.7rem`.

The render section currently looks like:

```jsx
<div ref={shellRef} className={`${styles.stageShell} ...`}>
    <div ref={ambientLightRef} className={styles.ambientLight} />
    <div className={styles.stageFrame}>
        <Stage ...> ... </Stage>
    </div>
    <PieMenu ... />
    <div className={styles.stageHud}>...</div>
    {/* NEW: Minimap goes here, before closing stageShell */}
    {viewport.scale > 1 && (
        <CanvasMinimap ... />
    )}
</div>
```

The conditional `viewport.scale > 1` satisfies the "only show when zoomed in" requirement.

